---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const PAUL_HEADSHOT = "https://pub-a4845709a76642e7943bcb8b80677531.r2.dev/main/paul.jpg";
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Meet the founders behind WorshipMetrics and the mission to make church technology easier to share, easier to learn, and more useful for ministry."
  canonical="/about"
>
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-indigo-50 via-white to-slate-50 px-4 py-24 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
      <span class="inline-block rounded-full bg-indigo-100 px-4 py-1 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-indigo-700">About WorshipMetrics</span>
      <h1 class="mt-6 text-4xl font-extrabold leading-tight tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-5xl">Technology should make ministry easier to share.</h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg text-slate-600">
        WorshipMetrics was built to help churches carry Sunday together, not leave it on one volunteer&apos;s shoulders. We believe good tools should invite more people in, including the next generation.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="pointer-events-none absolute -top-32 -right-32 h-96 w-96 rounded-full bg-indigo-200 opacity-20 blur-3xl"></div>
    <div class="pointer-events-none absolute -bottom-20 -left-20 h-72 w-72 rounded-full bg-violet-300 opacity-20 blur-3xl"></div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-white px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900">It started with a pastor&apos;s question.</h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
        Rev. Andrew Esqueda had tried every available tool to track attendance at First Presbyterian Church of West Chester. Nothing fit. So he brought the problem to his community. With cameras already installed for livestreaming, an idea formed: use those same tools to help the church understand what was really happening on Sunday without adding more work.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
        What started as a local experiment became a broader conviction. Church technology should not just create better dashboards. It should make ministry easier to share, easier to teach, and easier to sustain.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-slate-50 px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
      <h2 class="text-center text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900">The people behind WorshipMetrics</h2>
      <div class="mt-14 grid gap-8 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm">
          <img src="/legacy-images/rev-andrew-esqueda.jpeg" alt="Rev. Andrew Esqueda" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="mb-6 aspect-[4/3] w-full rounded-2xl object-cover" />
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Rev. Andrew Esqueda</h3>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm font-medium text-indigo-600">Co-Founder & Visionary</p>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
            Andrew gives WorshipMetrics its ministry logic. This was never about software for its own sake. It was about helping churches care for people well and build systems that serve the mission instead of exhausting the volunteers carrying it.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/rev-andrew-esqueda/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="mt-5 inline-block text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800">LinkedIn →</a>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm">
          <img src={PAUL_HEADSHOT} alt="Paul Richards" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="mb-6 aspect-[4/3] w-full rounded-2xl object-cover" />
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Paul Richards</h3>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm font-medium text-indigo-600">Co-Founder & Technology Lead</p>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
            Paul spent years building camera technology and asking a deeper question: what if these tools could help churches more directly? That question led to a product built around real Sunday workflows and around the belief that AV ministry should be accessible to anyone who wants to contribute.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/paulrichards87/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="mt-5 inline-block text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800">LinkedIn →</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-indigo-50 px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
      <span class="inline-block rounded-full bg-indigo-100 px-4 py-1 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-indigo-700">Our mission</span>
      <h2 class="mt-6 text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900">Technology should serve the sacred, not complicate it.</h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
        WorshipMetrics exists to help churches make streaming easier, share the Sunday workload, and create more meaningful places for people to serve. We think a healthy church should be able to bring new volunteers in, train them well, and trust them with real responsibility.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-14 grid max-w-5xl gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
      {[
        {
          title: "Ministry comes first",
          body: "Every feature has to help a real church carry real ministry better, not just add more software vocabulary.",
        },
        {
          title: "Technology should bring people in",
          body: "The right product does not just help the tech director. It gives students, new volunteers, and curious helpers a place to start.",
        },
        {
          title: "Every church deserves great tools",
          body: "Powerful and easy-to-learn tools should not be reserved for the biggest ministries with the biggest budgets.",
        },
      ].map(({ title, body }) => (
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-indigo-100 bg-white p-7 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">{title}</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600">{body}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-white px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-8 text-center shadow-sm sm:p-10">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-indigo-600">A belief we take seriously</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl">AV ministry should be accessible to anyone who wants to contribute.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-600 sm:text-lg">
        That is part of why the AV Club idea matters so much to us. The church should have better ways to invite younger people into meaningful service instead of assuming the booth belongs to a tiny circle of experts forever.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8"><a href="/av-club" class="btn-primary">See the AV Club vision</a></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-white px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900">Have questions? Talk directly with Paul.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-slate-600">
        <a href="mailto:paul@worshipmetrics.com" class="text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800">paul@worshipmetrics.com</a>
        {" · "}
        <a href="tel:9109677447" class="text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800">910-WORSHIP (910-967-7447)</a>
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-col items-center justify-center gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:flex-wrap">
        <a href="/discovery-call" class="inline-block rounded-xl bg-indigo-600 px-8 py-3.5 text-base font-semibold text-white shadow-md transition hover:bg-indigo-700">Book a demo</a>
        <a href="/av-club" class="btn-outline">Talk about launching an AV Club</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
